To accomplish this task, you can use the `ifstream` class in C++ to open and read the text file, and then iterate through each line of the file using a `string` variable. Here's an example program that counts the number of occurrences of the word "example" in a text file called "example.txt":

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>

int main() {
    std::ifstream file("example.txt");
    std::string line;
    int count = 0;

    if (file.is_open()) {
        while (std::getline(file, line)) {
            if (line.find("example") != std::string::npos) {
                count++;
            }
        }
    }

    std::cout << "The word 'example' occurred " << count << " times in the file." << std::endl;

    file.close();

    return 0;
}
```

This program first includes the necessary headers for input/output, file input/output, and strings. It then declares a `file` variable of type `std::ifstream`, which will be used to open and read the text file. A `line` variable of type `std::string` is declared to store each line of the file, and an `int` variable named `count` is initialized to 0 to keep track of the number of occurrences of the word "example".

The program then checks if the file was successfully opened using the `is_open()` function. If the file can be opened, the program enters a `while` loop that reads each line of the file using `std::getline()` and stores it in the `line` variable. The `find()` function of the `line` string is then used to check if the line contains the word "example". If it does, the `count` variable is incremented.

Finally, the program prints the number of occurrences of the word "example" using `std::cout`, closes the file using the `close()` function, and returns 0 to indicate successful completion.

